Problem Statement

Context

AllLife Bank is a US bank that has a growing customer base. The majority of these customers are liability customers (depositors) with varying sizes of deposits. The number of customers who are also borrowers (asset customers) is quite small, and the bank is interested in expanding this base rapidly to bring in more loan business and in the process, earn more through the interest on loans. In particular, the management wants to explore ways of converting its liability customers to personal loan customers (while retaining them as depositors).

A campaign that the bank ran last year for liability customers showed a healthy conversion rate of over 9% success. This has encouraged the retail marketing department to devise campaigns with better target marketing to increase the success ratio.

You as a Data scientist at AllLife bank have to build a model that will help the marketing department to identify the potential customers who have a higher probability of purchasing the loan.

Objective

To predict whether a liability customer will buy personal loans, to understand which customer attributes are most significant in driving purchases, and identify which segment of customers to target more.

Data Dictionary

  • ID: Customer ID
  • Age: Customers age in completed years
  • Experience: #years of professional experience
  • Income: Annual income of the customer (in thousand dollars)
  • ZIP Code: Home Address ZIP code.
  • Family: the Family size of the customer
  • CCAvg: Average spending on credit cards per month (in thousand dollars)
  • Education: Education Level. 1: Undergrad; 2: Graduate;3: Advanced/Professional
  • Mortgage: Value of house mortgage if any. (in thousand dollars)
  • Personal_Loan: Did this customer accept the personal loan offered in the last campaign? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • Securities_Account: Does the customer have securities account with the bank? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • CD_Account: Does the customer have a certificate of deposit (CD) account with the bank? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • Online: Do customers use internet banking facilities? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • CreditCard: Does the customer use a credit card issued by any other Bank (excluding All life Bank)? (0: No, 1: Yes)

# defining a function to compute different metrics to check performance of a classification model built using sklearn
# define classification model (Decision tree model) function
# Check performance of the model (use sklearn library)
# Calculate different metrics to check performance of classification model
def model_performance_classification(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check classification model performance

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    recall = recall_score(target, pred)  # to compute Recall
    precision = precision_score(target, pred)  # to compute Precision
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred)  # to compute F1-score

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {"Accuracy": acc, "Recall": recall, "Precision": precision, "F1": f1,},
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf
In[19]:
def plot_confusion_matrix(model, predictors, target):
    """
    To plot the confusion_matrix with percentages

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """
    # Predict the target values using the provided model and predictors
    y_pred = model.predict(predictors)

    # Compute the confusion matrix comparing the true target values with the predicted values
    cm = confusion_matrix(target, y_pred)

    # Create labels for each cell in the confusion matrix with both count and percentage
    labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ["{0:0.0f}".format(item) + "\n{0:.2%}".format(item / cm.flatten().sum())]
            for item in cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(2, 2)    # reshaping to a matrix

    # Set the figure size for the plot
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))

    # Plot the confusion matrix as a heatmap with the labels
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt="")

    # Add a label to the y-axis
    plt.ylabel("True label")

    # Add a label to the x-axis
    plt.xlabel("Predicted label")

** Observation **

  • The focus is to maximize the F1 Score to ensure that we reduce both the chances of approving non-credible applications as well as rejecting credible ones.

** Observation**

  • Original tree created is too complex. We will use pre pruning technique to make it less complex.
In[30]:
max_depth_values = np.arange(2, 11, 2) #output [2,4,6,8,10]
max_leaf_nodes_values = np.arange(10, 51, 10)  #output [10,20,30,40,50]
min_samples_split_values = np.arange(10, 51, 10) #output [10,20,30,40,50]

# initialize variables to store the best model and its performance
best_estimator = None
best_score_diff = float('inf')
best_test_score = 0.0

# iterate over all combinations of the specified parameter values
for max_depth in max_depth_values:
    for max_leaf_nodes in max_leaf_nodes_values:
        for min_samples_split in min_samples_split_values:

            # initialize the tree with the current set of parameters
            estimator = DecisionTreeClassifier(
                max_depth=max_depth,
                max_leaf_nodes=max_leaf_nodes,
                min_samples_split=min_samples_split,
                random_state=42
            )

            # fit the model to the training data
            estimator.fit(X_train, y_train)

            # make predictions on the training and test sets
            y_train_pred = estimator.predict(X_train)
            y_test_pred = estimator.predict(X_test)

            # calculate F1 scores for training and test sets
            train_f1_score = f1_score(y_train, y_train_pred)
            test_f1_score = f1_score(y_test, y_test_pred)

            # calculate the absolute difference between training and test F1 scores
            score_diff = abs(train_f1_score - test_f1_score)

            # update the best estimator and best score if the current one has a smaller score difference
            if score_diff < best_score_diff:
                best_score_diff = score_diff
                best_estimator = estimator

In[44]:
# Initialize an empty list to store the decision tree classifiers
clfs = []

# Iterate over each ccp_alpha value extracted from cost complexity pruning path
for ccp_alpha in ccp_alphas:
    # Create an instance of the DecisionTreeClassifier
    clf = DecisionTreeClassifier(ccp_alpha=ccp_alpha, random_state=1)

    # Fit the classifier to the training data
    clf.fit(X_train, y_train)

    # Append the trained classifier to the list
    clfs.append(clf)

# Print the number of nodes in the last tree along with its ccp_alpha value
print(
    "Number of nodes in the last tree is {} with ccp_alpha {}".format(
        clfs[-1].tree_.node_count, ccp_alphas[-1]
    )
)

Number of nodes in the last tree is 1 with ccp_alpha 0.056364969335601575

Observation: Remove the last element in clfs and ccp_alphas as it corresponds to a trivial tree with only one node.

for clf in clfs:
    # Predict labels for the training set using the current decision tree classifier
    pred_train = clf.predict(X_train)

    # Calculate the F1 score for the training set predictions compared to true labels
    f1_train = f1_score(y_train, pred_train)

    # Append the calculated F1 score to the train_f1_scores list
    train_f1_scores.append(f1_train)

Actionable Insights and Business Recommendations

Actionable Insights and Business Recommendations Data Analysis

  • There are 5000 rows and 14 columns in the dataset
  • There are 14 numerical and 0 categorical variable in the data
  • Average age of users is 45 years (minimum 23 and maximum 67)
  • Mortgage - Value of mortgage in thousands: More than 50% of the users have no mortgage.
  • There is no data with null value *There are no duplicates in the dataset Univariate Analysis
  • Age and Experience are evenly distributed following somewhat similar distribution.
  • Income is right skewed with 75% of the users having income less than 100K.
  • There are some outliers with income more than ~180K
  • Family size is evenly distributed ranging from 1 to 4
  • Average spending on credit card per month (CCAvg) is right skewed data with 75% users spending <2500 per month, with some outliers.
  • Users having Personal loan, Securities Account, CD Account are less in number (~10%)
  • Users having credit cards are more (~30-35%) compared to other accounts
  • Mortgage - Value of mortgage in thousands: More than 50% of the users have no mortgage.
  • Experience seems to have negative value that will need correction later. ** Bivariate Analysis **
  • Age and Experience fields are strongly correlated (almost the same pattern), so we can drop either of the two fields during data processing
  • Positive correlation between Income and users having personal loan as well as spending more on credit cards per month (CCAvg)
  • Users approved for one product are more likely to have approval for other products as well. Like person who is approved for personal loan is likely to get approved for credit card, securities account and CD Account.
  • Users having CCAvg<3 are more likely to get rejected for personal loan
  • Users having income<100k are more likely to get rejected for personal loan
  • Users not having any CD account are more likely to get rejected for personal loan
  • Users having education level 1 (Undergrad) are more likely to get rejected for personal loan
  • CCAvg and Income are positively correlated
  • Experience and Age are almost same and following same distribution. Fields like Income, CCAvg, Education level can be used for decision tree m modeling Users with a income of more than 600K are more likely to have their application approved. ** Data Preprocessing **
  • There are no fields with missing data
  • All the rows of data have unique data
  • Applicants with higher income have higher chances of getting credit card approval.
  • Users with income > 100K are more likely to get a loan approved.
  • Users with higher Education have higher chances of getting loan approval.
  • Correcting the data for experience changing negative values
  • Dropping the Experience field as Age and Experience are almost same in the distribution
  • Data is divided into test and train sets (70% and 30%)
  • Train dataset have ~9.45% approval
  • Test dataset have ~9.93% approval (comparable to train dataset) ** Decision Tree Model Building **
  • Four trees are compared in the analysis:
    • Original tree without pruning gives high Recall, F1, Precision scores, which might be due to overfitting
    • After pre-pruning, we see slight decline in Recall, F1, Precision scores, but the tree is less complex than the original tree
    • Post-pruning (using F1 score), gives better scores of Recall, F1, Precision scores and also the tree is less complex than the pre-pruned tree.
    • Post-pruning (using recall score), declines the score slightly for Recall, F1, precision however the tree has reduced complexity significantly.

** Summary **

  • Running the model without pre/post pruning gives a high score which is expected due to the overfitting nature of decision trees. To find the tree that is fairly same in the scores (Precision, Recall, F1), and yet very simple with limited nodes, it is recommended to use post-pruning model based on Recall that gives generalized behavior.
  1. Original Tree
  • dtree_model1 is defined as original model
    • Gini Score Order top-4 features (Education > Income > Family > CCAvg)
    • Accuracy, Recall, Precision, F1 for train data (1.0, 1.0, 1.0, 1.0) and for test data (0.978667, 0.892617, 0.892617, 0.892617)
    • Running the model without pre/post pruning gives a high score which is expected due to the overfitting nature of decision trees
    • Above matrix says that FP=0 and FN=0 meaning the training data perfectly fits (may have possible overfitting), that needs evaluation later
    • The focus is to maximize the F1 Score to ensure that we reduce both the chances of approving non-credible applications as well as rejecting credible ones.
  • The model works perfectly fine on training data with F1=1. The model has perfect precision and recall, meaning it correctly classifies all positive cases.
  • Recall=1, meaning the classifier correctly fits all the positive instances in the dataset. There are no false negatives (FN).
  • As the tree is very complex (depth =11, #nodes =95), there is a need to pre-prune and even post-prune
  1. Tree After Pre-Pruning
  • After pre-pruning, the tree is simplified
    • Gini Score Order top-4 features (Education > Income > Family > CCAvg) which is same as original tree
    • Accuracy, Recall, Precision, F1 for train data (0.988857, 0.915408, 0.964968, 0.939535) and for test data (0.982, 0.872483, 0.942029, 0.905923)
    • With pre-pruning, the model has improved the Accuracy, Precision and F1 score on test data.
    • There is slight dip in recall value (0.89 to 0.87) on test data, but overall tree is much simpler.
  • The tree can be compared with post-pruning to see if we have simpler tree without losing the predictability scores
  1. Tree After Post-Pruning using top F1 score is observed that at alpha = ~0.007 the tree seems to have reached the smallest size which is underfitting the data.
  • Gini Score Order top-4 features (Education > Income > Family > CCAvg) which is same as original tree and pre-pruning.
  • Accuracy, Recall, Precision, F1 for train data (0.996, 0.97281, 0.984709, 0.978723) and for test data (0.984667, 0.892617, 0.95, 0.920415).
  • With post-pruning, the model has improved the Accuracy, Precision and F1 score on test data compared to pre-pruned tree.
  • We can see that the recall value in test dataset is decreased from .97 (train) to 0.89 (test), which means we might be leaving some eligible customers.
  • The tree can be pruned based on recall to increase focus on True positives.
  1. Tree After Post-Pruning using recall score
  • The best performing model was derived from the Decision Tree Model where the original tree was post-pruned using highest recall (via ccp_alpha=0.056).
  • Gini Score Order top-3 features (Income > Family > Education) which is changed from previous three trees. Dropping one criteria (CCAvg which was lowest contributor in decision making), along with Income becoming the top influencing feature.
  • Accuracy, Recall, Precision, F1 for train data (0.964286, 0.924471, 0.753695, 0.830393) and for test data (0.963333, 0.892617, 0.773256, 0.82866). With post-pruning based on recall, the recall value of test dataset is retained 0.89, yet ensuring the tree is simplified considerably
  • Due to simplicity, testing the model on random 20th row gives the result in ~5ms and 95% confident that the applicant is likely to get approved if apply. We can conclude the post-prunned model of the decision tree perfoms best as it gives the best recall scores

  • The best performing model was derived from the Decision Tree Model where the original tree was post-pruned using highest recall (via ccp_alpha=0.056). The recall value based on this is:

dtree4_train_perf_tuned = 0.924471 dtree4_test_perf_tuned_post2 = 0.892617

Features that most affects the decision to accept a personal loan are listed below:

  • Income: Higher income individuals are more likely to be approved for personal loan
  • Education: Customers with Education level 2 and above are more likely to be approved for personal loan
  • Family: As familly size grows, customers are more willing to accept personal loan
  • CCAvg: Customers having higher average monthly spending are more willing to accept personal loan
  • In the final model, top 3 features are considered to simplify, getting the 96.43% right prediction (training data) and 96.34% right prediction on test data.

Recommendation

  • The business marketing team is recommended to focus on Income, Education, Family size as primary features to create their target audience.
  • Marketing team must review personal profiles of individuals to consider them for personal loan
  • Marketing can also give offer to these individuals to attract them to apply for a loan (with more likelihood of approval) -
  • Personal Loan Campaign Viable condition for marketing team to create their test case may be (Income > 98.5 and Education = 2 or 3) Or (Income > 98.5, Education = 1, Family > 2).
  • These segment represents customers are most likely to apply and get approved for loan.
  • Customers who uses online can be targeted using digital channels (~60% users who got approved). Hence online marketing campaign is highly recommended
